  "prompt": "In Tagalog, what are the rules for using Nang and Ng?",
  "response": "In Tagalog, \"ng\" and \"nang\" are both common particles, but they have different uses:\n\n\"Ng\" (Particle):\n1. Used to show possession\nExample: Bahay ng tao (House of the person)\n\n2. Used as a linker between words\nExample: Librong pula (Red book)\n\n3. Can mean \"of\" or indicate a relationship\nExample: Kaibigan ng pamilya (Friend of the family)\n\n\"Nang\" (Particle):\n1. Used to mean \"when\" or indicate time\nExample: Nang umaga (In the morning)\n\n2. Used as an adverb or to modify verbs\nExample: Nang mabilis (Quickly)\n\n3. Used to indicate manner or way of doing something\nExample: Nang maingat (Carefully)\n\nKey differences:\n- \"Ng\" is primarily used for possession and linking\n- \"Nang\" is used for time, manner, and adverbial functions\n\nNote that pronunciation can be similar, so context is important in distinguishing between them.\n\nThese rules help structure Tagalog sentences and clarify relationships between words.",
